\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the modern robotic fleets deployed in search and rescue (SAR) missions,
 the decision-making and path-planning coordination do not realistically represent the ground truth of open-world environments.
 Current coordination strategies fail to account for the diverse locomotion capabilities required to navigate dynamic and unpredictable terrains,
 such as those encountered during natural disasters (e.g.,
 flooding,
 torrential rain,
 or urban-forest interfaces).
 Robotic engineers need to employ a fleet that incorporates all types of robotic locomotion to surpass these limitations [].
 These locomotion types include Legged,
 Aerial,
 Nautical,
 Driven,
 and Surface robots.
 Each type of robot should be able to inspect the mission site and perform actions in the environment,
 such as delivering a care package or providing immediate aid to individuals in need.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the potential of such diverse fleets,
 the literature does not adequately address scenarios requiring the coordinated deployment of these locomotion types.
 Hence,
 each agent's traversability capability and assessments of risks when navigating terrain should be confronted.
 This research seeks to bridge these gaps by investigating a novel framework for coordinating heterogeneous robotic fleets to ensure operational efficacy in realistic,
 open-world environments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work will investigate the utilisation of a centralised mission planning algorithm derived from a traversability risk assessment framework.
 The framework is a probabilistic risk model estimating the sum of all traversability risks in a robotic agent's environment that would damage the robot or impede the mission.
 The algorithm will coordinate a heterogeneous multi-robotic fleet deployment containing differing locomotion types.
 Therefore,
 a lower traversability risk would mean a more suitable terrain for a specified locomotion type.
 The fleet coordination and agent distribution will be based on appropriate terrain for each locomotion type,
 encouraging faster search times for survivors whilst being capable of rearranging robots that can provide immediate relief while considering power management for navigation.
 Ensuring post-calamity environments are traversable and physical aid can be distributed to survivors promptly to prolong their chances of survival.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There has been extensive research on cooperative robotics in SAR operations,
 where a heterogeneous group of robots (mainly a pair of two differing locomotion types) would collaboratively search environments together to reach survivors of disasters...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These robotic fleet applications demonstrate how a heterogeneous multi-robotic system offering different locomotion utilities is more optimised for realistic open-world environments,
 Thus expanding the scope and quality of tasks SAR robotic systems could execute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 the amount of research investigating fleets utilising all four locomotion types is extremely limited.
 To the best of our knowledge,
 this is the first study to examine the coordination of a heterogeneous robot fleet containing all methods of locomotion.
 The lack of research derives from hostile environments,
 computational complexity,
 and the exponential chance of faults that arise when multiple robots synchronously operate together.
 Current experimental studies focus on communication and bandwidth constraints within robot fleets,
 as well as the synchronisation of individual robot systems into fleets,
 such as path planning and mapping,
 With the works tending towards deploying fully autonomous heterogeneous multi-robotic teams for SAR missions with active perception.
 Assuming the relief of these constraints,
 open research questions emerge,
 portraying critical directions to advance the broader adoption of multi-robot systems in SAR.
 This work addresses the following gaps in the research:
\end_layout

