\begin_layout Standard
The potential of the systems is heightened when united under one framework,
 allowing for accurate,
 standardised comparisons of probability and bids in market-based decision-making.
 Standardisation will allow for fair bidding in task allocation as all robots will have a consistent evaluation metric,
 giving the fleet more scalability and flexibility.
 Additionally,
 one framework will allow future work to consider decentralised coordination methods.
 By mitigating the constrained locomotions of the system,
 the robot fleet will be able to distribute perception data to robots that could not previously access terrain information outside of their peripheral sensor vision;
 for example,
 an Unmanned Ground Vehicle (UGV) being unable to scan and map sharp cliffs in its vicinity seen in [],
 the use of a Unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) would be able to monitor the drop-off with minimal risk and be able to merge maps with the UGV to fill in the gaps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore,
 utilising a heterogeneous fleet that can interact with and traverse all environments will increase the chance of finding the targets in real-world applications as more of the environment becomes accessible.
 The significant map updates and replanning potential also mean that the fleet can reorganise itself to evaluate the terrain information and navigate key agents that can provide triage and medical aid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Aims & Objectives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This research aims to develop a traversability risk assessment framework that can be incorporated into the decision-making algorithms of heterogeneous robotic fleets during search and rescue missions.
 By analysing terrain traversability across four locomotion types,
 this framework will enhance the effectiveness of heterogeneous robotic fleets in disaster scenarios,
 enabling coordinated efforts to reduce search times and deliver critical aid in complex,
 dynamic environments with realistic obstacles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following research objectives for this report are initialised:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Develop a traversability risk assessment framework that is able to represent all physical terrain obstructions that would impede a robot fleet as a summed probabilistic traversability risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Extend the framework to include aquatic and aerial traversability risks to enable a heterogeneous fleet mission of different locomotion types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider non-physical environmental factors such as temperature,
 humidity and radiation in the probabilistic risk model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Produce a centralised mission planning algorithm to coordinate the fleet.
 Introduce more robotic agents of differing locomotion types and consider how the system will handle and distribute them efficiently based on suitable terrain for each locomotion type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simulate the framework in urban,
 rural,
 and hybrid disaster scenarios,
 portraying that the algorithm works for a heterogeneous fleet of robots with all locomotion types and can provide immediate relief to survivors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Demonstrate that the framework works for a heterogeneous robotic fleet in urban-rural hybrid scenarios with one combination of locomotion types.
\end_layout

